Wash and dry produce.

Quarter @lime{1}. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{4}, separating whites from 
greens. Thinly slice one @jalapeño{1} into rounds; mince remaining @jalapeño{1}, 
removing ribs and seeds for less heat. Dice @tomato{2}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @sour cream{6%tablespoon} with a squeeze of lime 
juice to taste. Add water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling 
consistency. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a #5- to 6-quart heavy-bottomed 
pot{} over medium-high heat. Add scallion whites and minced jalapeño to taste. 
Season with salt. Cook, stirring, until softened, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Add @ground turkey{20%ounce} and @Southwest spice blend{2%tablespoon} to pot 
with aromatics; season with salt and pepper. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, 
until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

> Ground Turkey is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.

Stir diced tomato, @tomato paste{2%tablespoon}, and @Tex-Mex paste{2%tablespoon} 
into pot; cook until slightly darkened in color, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add @black beans{2%15oz cans} and their liquid, @chicken stock concentrate{4}, 
½ cup water (1 cup for 8 servings), salt, and pepper; stir to combine. Bring to 
a simmer and cook until thickened, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> TIP: If chili is too thick, add a splash of water.

Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Divide chili between #bowls{}. Top with lime crema, scallion greens, and as 
much sliced jalapeño as you like. Serve.

> These top-notch turkey-fied bowls are adorned with some delicious fixings: 
> smoky red pepper crema and sliced jalapeño. If you've got some on hand, why 
> not sprinkle some crumbled @?tortilla chips{} on top for crunch?